The scoring logic, as shown in calculate_pow_score.py and calculate_score.py, primarily considers the results of PoW challenges (e.g., challenge successes, failures, difficulty, and execution time).
The PoW process, detailed in pow.py, generates challenges for miners and evaluates their responses to these challenges. Success in these challenges and the efficiency of the response (how quickly and accurately the challenge is met) significantly impact the miner's score. The machine specs (CPUs, GPUs, RAM, and hard disk information) are collected and logged, as seen in scripts like specs.py and through the process in allocate.py.
The specs are crucial for the allocation process, ensuring that tasks are assigned to miners with the appropriate resources to handle them. This is seen in the allocation logic, where machine specs are considered to determine if a miner meets the requirements for a particular task. Although they don't directly factor into the scoring algorithm, they are critical for the allocation process, which, in turn, determines which miners are eligible to receive tasks and potentially earn rewards. Therefore, while not a direct component of the scoring function, specs are integral to the operational efficiency and fairness of the network.

if you're getting the connection error in pm2 logs when running miner.py, i would run `docker ps` inside your subtensor folder to check its running properly. also run `sudo ufw status` to see what ports the firewall has allowed - i see port 22, 30333 and the ports I specified to open during ufw install as being open when i run it. it is 2345:4532 as an example in the neural internet guide (https://docs.neuralinternet.ai/products/subnet-27-compute/bittensor-compute-subnet-miner-setup). then run the miner.py script for local subtensor - `pm2 start ./neurons/miner.py --name MINER --interpreter python3 -- --netuid 27 --subtensor.network local --wallet.name COLDKEYNAME --wallet.hotkey HOTKEYNAME --axon.port xxxx --logging.debug --miner.blacklist.force_validator_permit --auto_update yes`.  --axon.port will be 2345 in the example guide and replace HOTKEYNAME and COLDKEYNAME with your hotkey and coldkey.

i had an issue when i setup my subtensor which got resolved by uninstalling it, reinstalling it and running `sudo ufw allow 30333/tcp`  in root, before starting the `sudo ./scripts/run/subtensor.sh -e docker --network mainnet --node-type lite` script. 

my `docker ps` returned this screenshot after doing that, which then worked for me. it seemed that you needed port 30333 open for it to run properly.

hope that helps.

You need to consider three ports if you want to run a local node successfully:
`9944` - Websocket. This port is used by bittensor. It only accepts connections from localhost. Make sure this port is firewalled off from the public domain.
`9933` - RPC. This port is opened, but not used.
`30333` - p2p socket. This port accepts connections from other subtensor nodes. Make sure your fw allow incoming traffic to this port. Make sure outbound traffic to port 30333 is allowed.
